			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Whistleblower reveals Big Pharma pressures researchers to only release &quot;positive&quot;
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1859431">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							Interestingly, every ACTUAL biochemist working for big pharma says that they REGULARLY publish their failures, because THAT'S WHAT 99% OF THEIR WORK *IS*.<br />
<br />
The pharma companies don't *WANT* their successes published because, by the time they get through the approval process, they only have about 5 years left on the patent with which to profit off of the drug.<br />
<br />
There was an AMA on Reddit a few weeks back from a guy who got out of big pharma biochem after 20 years in the business due to a buyout and a plant closing, but he said almost NOONE who works in big pharma biochem will get so much as a SINGLE success over the course of their ENTIRE CAREER.<br />
<br />
He worked 20 years and his only success was an extremely mild one. I think it improved uptake of something existing by, like, 3%. Whatever it was, it was so minor that it wasn't even deemed worthy of pursuit.<br />
<br />
So, technically, they publish their failures all the time, it's just that those failures never ever make it to market.<br />
<br />
It's literally shit like &quot;we found this compound interacts with this other compound in this way, which we'd never seen before. It doesn't do anything even remotely useful as far as we can tell, but it's kinda interesting that it acts differently.&quot;<br />
<br />
Now, that being said, the article's point is more related to shit like Vioxx, which we're pretty sure had known nasty side effects before they were forced to take it off of the market and got sued for it, but the article is a TAD misleading when you take the whole picture into account.<br />
<br />
Yes, big pharma are a bunch of crooks who will do ALMOST ANYTHING to protect one of their precious revenue generators once it's on the market, but far and away, the glut of information published by the biochemists who work for big pharma is a massive laundry list of failures.<br />
<br />
Big pharma just doesn't mind THAT kind of publishing, because it's not putting any of their revenue-generators at risk. It's just a bunch of doctorates saying &quot;My gluten-free flan collapsed in a cupboard. It also collapsed on the counter. Six months later, the next one collapsed on the windowsill. This, however, does not say anything conclusive about this particular gluten-free flan recipe. It just collapsed under certain circumstances.&quot;
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
